# Deployment and Operations Guide

For a short command index and links to READMEs, see **`AGENTS.md`** at the repository root. This rule is the long-form operations reference.

## Deployment Methods

### Method 1: Deploy Script (Recommended)

```bash
# Deploy to dev environment (default); subcommands: b=build, d=deploy, bd=both
python scripts/deploy.py -e dev d all

# Deploy specific service
python scripts/deploy.py -e dev d api
python scripts/deploy.py -e dev d frontend

# Build and deploy (rebuilds container / image first)
python scripts/deploy.py -e dev bd api
python scripts/deploy.py -e dev bd event-handler

# Production deployment
python scripts/deploy.py -e production d all
```

### Method 2: Direct Kustomize

```bash
# Preview resources
kubectl kustomize kubernetes/overlays/dev

# Apply to cluster
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev

# Apply specific service overlay
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/api
```

## Deployment Order

Critical: Deploy in dependency order to avoid startup failures.

```bash
# 1. Core infrastructure (databases, messaging)
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/postgresql
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/redis
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/nats
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/kueue

# Wait for readiness
kubectl wait --for=condition=available deployment/postgresql -n recon
kubectl wait --for=condition=available deployment/nats -n recon
kubectl wait --for=condition=available deployment/redis -n recon

# 2. Configuration
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/config

# 3. Application services
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/api
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/frontend
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/event-handler

# 4. Job templates (not running services)
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/runner
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev/worker
```

## Environment Selection

| Environment | Overlay Path | Cluster | Use Case |
|-------------|--------------|---------|----------|
| dev | `overlays/dev/` | dev | Local development, testing |
| production | `overlays/production/` | prod | Production deployment |
| vrev | `overlays/vrev/` | vrev | VRev-specific configuration |

## Common Operations

### View Pod Status
```bash
kubectl get pods -n recon
kubectl get pods -n recon -l app=api
kubectl get pods -n recon -o wide  # With node info
```

### View Logs
```bash
# Deployment logs
kubectl logs -n recon deployment/api
kubectl logs -n recon deployment/api -f  # Follow
kubectl logs -n recon deployment/api --previous  # Previous container

# Pod logs
kubectl logs -n recon {pod-name}
kubectl logs -n recon {pod-name} -c {container}  # Specific container
```

### Restart Deployment
```bash
# Rolling restart
kubectl rollout restart deployment/api -n recon

# Force recreation
kubectl delete pod -n recon -l app=api
```

### Scale Deployment
```bash
kubectl scale deployment/api -n recon --replicas=3
```

### Port Forwarding
```bash
# API
kubectl port-forward -n recon svc/api 8000:8000

# NATS
kubectl port-forward -n recon svc/nats 4222:4222

# PostgreSQL
kubectl port-forward -n recon svc/postgresql 5432:5432
```

### Execute Commands
```bash
# Shell into pod
kubectl exec -it -n recon deployment/api -- /bin/bash

# Run command
kubectl exec -n recon deployment/api -- python -c "print('hello')"

# NATS CLI
kubectl exec -n recon deployment/nats -- nats stream ls
```

## Job Operations

### View Runner Jobs
```bash
kubectl get jobs -n recon -l app=runner
kubectl get jobs -n recon --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp
```

### View Job Logs
```bash
# Get pods for job
kubectl get pods -n recon -l job-name={job-name}

# View logs
kubectl logs -n recon job/{job-name}
```

### Clean Up Completed Jobs
```bash
# Delete completed jobs older than 1 hour
kubectl delete jobs -n recon --field-selector status.successful=1

# Delete all failed jobs
kubectl delete jobs -n recon --field-selector status.failed=1
```

## Secret Management

### Create Secrets
```bash
# PostgreSQL credentials
kubectl create secret generic postgres-secret -n recon \
    --from-literal=postgres-root-username=admin \
    --from-literal=postgres-root-password='secure-password'

# JWT secrets
kubectl create secret generic jwt-secret -n recon \
    --from-literal=jwt-secret-key='your-jwt-secret' \
    --from-literal=refresh-secret-key='your-refresh-secret'

# Internal service token
kubectl create secret generic internal-service-secret -n recon \
    --from-literal=token='internal-service-api-key'
```

### Update Secrets
```bash
# Delete and recreate
kubectl delete secret jwt-secret -n recon
kubectl create secret generic jwt-secret -n recon \
    --from-literal=jwt-secret-key='new-jwt-secret' \
    --from-literal=refresh-secret-key='new-refresh-secret'
```

### View Secrets
```bash
# List secrets
kubectl get secrets -n recon

# Decode secret value
kubectl get secret postgres-secret -n recon -o jsonpath='{.data.postgres-root-password}' | base64 -d
```

## ConfigMap Operations

### View ConfigMaps
```bash
kubectl get configmap -n recon
kubectl describe configmap recon-config -n recon
kubectl get configmap recon-config -n recon -o yaml
```

### Update ConfigMap
```bash
# Edit directly
kubectl edit configmap recon-config -n recon

# Apply from file
kubectl apply -f kubernetes/base/config/service-config.yaml -n recon
```

## Troubleshooting

### Pod Not Starting
```bash
# Check events
kubectl describe pod -n recon {pod-name}

# Check resource quotas
kubectl describe resourcequota -n recon

# Check node resources
kubectl top nodes
kubectl describe node {node-name}
```

### Container CrashLoopBackOff
```bash
# Check previous logs
kubectl logs -n recon {pod-name} --previous

# Check container exit code
kubectl describe pod -n recon {pod-name} | grep -A5 "Last State"
```

### Network Issues
```bash
# Check service endpoints
kubectl get endpoints -n recon

# Test DNS resolution
kubectl exec -n recon deployment/api -- nslookup nats

# Check network policies
kubectl get networkpolicies -n recon
kubectl describe networkpolicy -n recon {policy-name}
```

### Image Pull Errors
```bash
# Check image name
kubectl describe pod -n recon {pod-name} | grep -A5 "Container ID"

# Verify image exists locally (for dev)
docker images | grep api

# Check registry credentials (for prod)
kubectl get secret regcred -n recon
```

## Monitoring

### Resource Usage
```bash
# Pod resources
kubectl top pods -n recon

# Container resources
kubectl top pods -n recon --containers

# Namespace total
kubectl describe resourcequota -n recon
```

### Health Checks
```bash
# Check probe status
kubectl describe pod -n recon {pod-name} | grep -A10 "Liveness"

# Manual health check
kubectl exec -n recon deployment/api -- curl -s localhost:8000/health
```

## Rollback

### Deployment Rollback
```bash
# View history
kubectl rollout history deployment/api -n recon

# Rollback to previous
kubectl rollout undo deployment/api -n recon

# Rollback to specific revision
kubectl rollout undo deployment/api -n recon --to-revision=2
```

### Full Environment Rollback
```bash
# Git revert to previous manifests
git log --oneline kubernetes/
git checkout {commit-hash} -- kubernetes/

# Reapply
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev
```

## Cleanup

### Remove All Resources
```bash
# Delete overlay resources
kubectl delete -k kubernetes/overlays/dev

# Delete namespace (removes everything)
kubectl delete namespace recon
```

### Prune Resources
```bash
# Remove resources not in manifests
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev --prune -l app.kubernetes.io/name=recon
```

## CI/CD Integration

### Dry Run Validation
```bash
# Validate manifests
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev --dry-run=client

# Server-side validation
kubectl apply -k kubernetes/overlays/dev --dry-run=server

# Diff against live
kubectl diff -k kubernetes/overlays/dev
```

### Automated Deployment
```bash
# In CI pipeline (ensure KUBECONFIG / kubeconfig paths match deploy.py expectations)
python scripts/deploy.py -e ${ENVIRONMENT} d all
```
